  "doc_id": "29625",
  "text": "The experiments described in this study were performed using an untargeted metabolomics workflow similar to Cho et al. [CITATION_1] , in which MS data were collected and statistical tools were used to identify notable features in the data. MALDI-MS data were used without retention time separation to identify significantly changing peaks. MALDI-MS experiments require very little sample (,10 mg), minimal sample preparation, and short analysis time; thus, this technique can be useful in differentiating cell or tissue types, where sample is limited. Indeed, a few studies have been reported using MALDI for such tissue types, including identifying primary cancer sites from analysis of metastatic lesions, cancer stage determination from gliomas, and intrasurgical normal/ cancer tissue discrimination [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Using these advanced MS approaches will lead the way in small molecule biomarker discovery and could potentially be used to determine treatment effectiveness at a very early stage.",
